1. Install Artifactory on EC2	Self-hosted JFrog on AWS VM

Here are the steps to install JFrog Artifactory (OSS or Pro) on an AWS EC2 instance:

1. Launch EC2 Instance
AMI: Ubuntu 22.04 LTS or Amazon Linux 2
Instance type: t3.medium minimum (4 GB RAM); t3.large or better for production
Storage: 30+ GB EBS (gp3)
Security Group: open ports 8081 (Artifactory) and 8082 (router/UI)

2. Connect & Install Prerequisites
ssh -i your-key.pem ubuntu@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>

# Update and install Java 17
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y openjdk-17-jdk curl gnupg2
java -version

3. Install Artifactory via APT (JFrog repo)
# Add JFrog GPG key and repo
curl -fsSL https://releases.jfrog.io/artifactory/api/gpg/key/public | \
  sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/jfrog.gpg

echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jfrog.gpg] \
  https://releases.jfrog.io/artifactory/artifactory-debs xenial contrib" | \
  sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jfrog.list

sudo apt update

# For OSS (free):
sudo apt install -y jfrog-artifactory-oss

# For Pro Trial:
# sudo apt install -y jfrog-artifactory-pro

4. Start & Enable Artifactory
sudo systemctl enable artifactory
sudo systemctl start artifactory
sudo systemctl status artifactory

5. Access the UI
Open in browser: http://<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>:8082/ui

Default credentials: admin / password
You'll be prompted to change the password on first login

6. (Optional) Reverse Proxy with Nginx + HTTPS
sudo apt install -y nginx certbot python3-certbot-nginx

# Configure nginx to proxy to localhost:8082
sudo tee /etc/nginx/sites-available/artifactory <<'EOF'
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name your-domain.example.com;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8082;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
EOF

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/artifactory /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t && sudo systemctl reload nginx

# TLS via Let's Encrypt
sudo certbot --nginx -d your-domain.example.com

7. Firewall (if UFW is active)
sudo ufw allow 8082/tcp   # direct access
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp
sudo ufw allow 443/tcp

Key Paths
Purpose	Path
Config	/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/etc/
Logs	/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/log/
Data/storage	/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/data/
For production, consider mounting an EBS volume at /var/opt/jfrog/artifactory before starting the service so artifact storage survives instance replacement.

